# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: active-filters
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:active-filters/active-filter] An **active filter** is a type of analog circuit implementing an electronic filter using active components, typically an amplifier.
[src:active-filters/active-filter] Amplifiers included in a filter design can be used to improve the cost, performance and predictability of a filter.
[src:active-filters/active-filter] An amplifier prevents the load impedance of the following stage from affecting the characteristics of the filter.
[src:active-filters/active-filter] An active filter can have complex poles and zeros without using a bulky or expensive inductor.
[src:active-filters/active-filter] The shape of the response, the Q (quality factor), and the tuned frequency can often be set with inexpensive variable resistors.
[src:active-filters/active-filter] In some active filter circuits, one parameter can be adjusted without affecting the others.
[src:active-filters/active-filter] Using active elements has some limitations.
[src:active-filters/active-filter] Basic filter design equations neglect the finite bandwidth of amplifiers.
[src:active-filters/active-filter] Available active devices have limited bandwidth, so they are often impractical at high frequencies.
[src:active-filters/active-filter] Amplifiers consume power and inject noise into a system.
[src:active-filters/active-filter] Certain circuit topologies may be impractical if no DC path is provided for bias current to the amplifier elements.
[src:active-filters/active-filter] Power handling capability is limited by the amplifier stages.
[src:active-filters/active-filter] Active filters can implement the same transfer functions as passive filters.
[src:active-filters/active-filter] where most of the offending rumble comes from a particular frequency).
[src:active-filters/active-filter] An active filter can have gain, increasing the power available in a signal compared to the input.
[src:active-filters/active-filter] Passive filters dissipate energy from a signal and cannot have a net power gain.
[src:active-filters/active-filter] This advantage may not be as important for active filters entirely integrated on a chip because the available capacitors have relatively low values and so require high value resistors which take up area of the integrated circuit.
[src:active-filters/active-filter] Active filters have good isolation between stages, and can provide high input impedance and low output impedance; this makes their characteristics independent of the source and load impedances.
[src:active-filters/active-filter] Multiple stages can be cascaded when desired to improve characteristics.
[src:active-filters/active-filter] In contrast, design of multiple-stage passive filters must take into account each stage's frequency-dependent loading of the preceding stage.
[src:active-filters/active-filter] It is feasible to make active filters tunable over a wide range, compared with passive filters.
[src:active-filters/active-filter] Since inductors are not used, filters can be made in a very compact size and do not produce or interact with magnetic fields that may be present.
[src:active-filters/active-filter] Compared with active filters, passive filters require no additional power supplies.
[src:active-filters/active-filter] The amplifying devices of an active filter must provide predictable gain and performance over the entire frequency range to be processed; the gain–bandwidth product of the amplifier will constrain the maximum frequency that can be used.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] The **Butterworth filter** is a type of signal processing filter designed to have a frequency response that is as flat as possible in the passband.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] It is also referred to as a **maximally flat magnitude filter**.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] It was first described in 1930 by the British engineer and physicist Stephen Butterworth in his paper entitled "On the Theory of Filter Amplifiers".
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] Butterworth had a reputation for solving very complex mathematical problems thought to be 'impossible'.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] At the time, filter design required a considerable amount of designer experience due to limitations of the theory then in use.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] The filter was not in common use for over 30 years after its publication.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] Such an ideal filter cannot be achieved, but Butterworth showed that successively closer approximations were obtained with increasing numbers of filter elements of the right values.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] At the time, filters generated substantial ripple in the passband, and the choice of component values was highly interactive.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] where $\omega$ is the angular frequency in radians per second and n is the number of poles in the filter—equal to the number of reactive elements in a passive filter.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] Its cutoff frequency (the half-power point of approximately −3 dB or a voltage gain of 1/√2 ≈ 0.7071) is normalized to 𝜔 = 1 radian per second.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] Butterworth only dealt with filters with an even number of poles in his paper, though odd-order filters can be created with the addition of a single-pole filter applied to the output of the even-order filter.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] He built his higher-order filters from 2-pole filters separated by vacuum tube amplifiers.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] His plot of the frequency response of 2-, 4-, 6-, 8-, and 10-pole filters is shown as A, B, C, D, and E in his original graph.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] Butterworth solved the equations for two-pole and four-pole filters, showing how the latter could be cascaded when separated by vacuum tube amplifiers and so enabling the construction of higher-order filters despite inductor losses.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] In 1930, low-loss core materials such as molypermalloy had not been discovered and air-cored audio inductors were rather lossy.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] Butterworth discovered that it was possible to adjust the component values of the filter to compensate for the winding resistance of the inductors.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] He used coil forms of 1.25 inches (32 mm) in diameter and 3 inches (76 mm) in length with plug-in terminals.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] Associated capacitors and resistors were contained inside the wound coil form.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] The coil formed part of the plate load resistor.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] Two poles were used per vacuum tube and RC coupling was used to the grid of the following tube.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] Butterworth also showed that the basic low-pass filter could be modified to give low-pass, high-pass, band-pass and band-stop functionality.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] The frequency response of the Butterworth filter is maximally flat (i.e., has no ripples) in the passband and rolls off towards zero in the stopband.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] When viewed on a logarithmic Bode plot, the response slopes off linearly towards negative infinity.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] A first-order filter's response rolls off at −6 dB per octave (−20 dB per decade) (all first-order lowpass filters have the same normalized frequency response).
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] A second-order filter decreases at −12 dB per octave, a third-order at −18 dB and so on.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] Butterworth filters have a monotonically changing magnitude function with $\omega$ , unlike other filter types that have non-monotonic ripple in the passband or the stopband.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] A simple example of a Butterworth filter is the third-order low-pass design shown in the figure on the right, with $C_{2}$ = 4/3 F, $R_{4}$ = 1 Ω, $L_{1}$ = 3/2 H, and $L_{3}$ = 1/2 H.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] The group delay is defined as the negative derivative of the phase shift with respect to angular frequency and is a measure of the distortion in the signal introduced by phase differences for different frequencies.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] The gain and the delay for this filter are plotted in the graph on the left.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] There are no ripples in the gain curve in either the passband or the stopband.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] The log of the absolute value of the transfer function $H(s)$ is plotted in complex frequency space in the second graph on the right.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] The function is defined by the three poles in the left half of the complex frequency plane.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] These are arranged on a circle of radius unity, symmetrical about the real s axis.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] The gain function will have three more poles on the right half-plane to complete the circle.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] By replacing each inductor with a capacitor and each capacitor with an inductor, a high-pass Butterworth filter is obtained.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] A band-pass Butterworth filter is obtained by placing a capacitor in series with each inductor and an inductor in parallel with each capacitor to form resonant circuits.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] The value of each new component must be selected to resonate with the old component at the frequency of interest.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] A band-stop Butterworth filter is obtained by placing a capacitor in parallel with each inductor and an inductor in series with each capacitor to form resonant circuits.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] The value of each new component must be selected to resonate with the old component at the frequency that is to be rejected.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] Like all filters, the typical prototype is the low-pass filter, which can be modified into a high-pass filter, or placed in series with others to form band-pass and band-stop filters, and higher order versions of these.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] where n is the order of filter, $\omega _{c}$ is the cutoff frequency (approximately the −3 dB frequency), and $G_{0}$ is the DC gain (gain at zero frequency).
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] It can be seen that as n approaches infinity, the gain becomes a rectangle function and frequencies below $\omega _{c}$ will be passed with gain $G_{0}$ , while frequencies above $\omega _{c}$ will be suppressed.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] For smaller values of n , the cutoff will be less sharp.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] We wish to determine the transfer function $H(s)$ where $s=\sigma +j\omega$ (from Laplace transform).
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] then, with $s=j\omega$ , we have the frequency response of the Butterworth filter.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] The n poles of this expression occur on a circle of radius $\omega _{c}$ at equally-spaced points, and symmetric around the negative real axis.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] For stability, the transfer function, $H(s)$ , is therefore chosen such that it contains only the poles in the negative real half-plane of s .
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] where $\textstyle {\prod }$ is the product of a sequence operator.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] The denominator is a Butterworth polynomial in s .
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] The Butterworth polynomials may be written in complex form as above, but are usually written with real coefficients by multiplying pole pairs that are complex conjugates, such as $s_{1}$ and $s_{n}$ .
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] The polynomials are normalized by setting $\omega _{c}=1$ .
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] Factors of Butterworth polynomials of order 1 through 10 are shown in the following table (to six decimal places).
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] Factors of Butterworth polynomials of order 1 through 6 are shown in the following table (Exact).
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] where the Greek letter phi ( $\varphi$ or $\phi$ ) represents the golden ratio.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] Transformation to other bandforms are also possible, see prototype filter.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] which is monotonically decreasing for all $\omega$ since the gain G is always positive.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] The gain function of the Butterworth filter therefore has no ripple.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] In other words, all derivatives of the gain up to but not including the 2 n -th derivative are zero at $\omega =0$ , resulting in "maximal flatness".
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] If the requirement to be monotonic is limited to the passband only and ripples are allowed in the stopband, then it is possible to design a filter of the same order, such as the inverse Chebyshev filter, that is flatter in the passband than the "maximally flat" Butterworth.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] To design a Butterworth filter using the minimum required number of elements, the minimum order of the Butterworth filter may be calculated as follows.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] are the pass band frequency and attenuation at that frequency in dB.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] are the stop band frequency and attenuation at that frequency in dB.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] is the minimum number of poles, the order of the filter.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] The cutoff attenuation for Butterworth filters is usually defined to be −3.01 dB.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] If it is desired to use a different attenuation at the cutoff frequency, then the following factor may be applied to each pole, whereupon the poles will continue to lie on a circle, but the radius will no longer be unity.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] The cutoff attenuation equation may be derived through algebraic manipulation of the Butterworth defining equation stated at the top of the page.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] is the relocated pole positioned to set the desired cutoff attenuation.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] 3.01 dB cutoff pole that lies on the unit circle.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] is the desired attenuation at the cutoff frequency in dB (1 dB, 10 dB, etc.).
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] is the number of poles, the order of the filter.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] There are several different filter topologies available to implement a linear analogue filter.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] The most often used topology for a passive realisation is the Cauer topology, and the most often used topology for an active realisation is the Sallen–Key topology.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] The Cauer topology uses passive components (shunt capacitors and series inductors) to implement a linear analog filter.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] The Butterworth filter having a given transfer function can be realised using a Cauer 1-form.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] The filter may start with a series inductor if desired, in which case the *Lk* are *k* odd and the *Ck* are *k* even.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] These formulae may usefully be combined by making both *Lk* and *Ck* equal to *gk*.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] That is, *gk* is the immittance divided by *s*.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] These formulae apply to a doubly terminated filter (that is, the source and load impedance are both equal to unity) with ωc = 1.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] This prototype filter can be scaled for other values of impedance and frequency.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] Voltage driven filters must start with a series element and current driven filters must start with a shunt element.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] These forms are useful in the design of diplexers and multiplexers.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] The Sallen–Key topology uses active and passive components (noninverting buffers, usually op amps, resistors, and capacitors) to implement a linear analog filter.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] Each Sallen–Key stage implements a conjugate pair of poles; the overall filter is implemented by cascading all stages in series.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] If there is a real pole (in the case where n is odd), this must be implemented separately, usually as an RC circuit, and cascaded with the active stages.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] We wish the denominator to be one of the quadratic terms in a Butterworth polynomial.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] This leaves two undefined component values that may be chosen at will.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] Butterworth lowpass filters with Sallen–Key topology of third and fourth order, using only one op amp, are described by Huelsman, and further single-amplifier Butterworth filters also of higher order are given by Jurišić et al.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] Digital implementations of Butterworth and other filters are often based on the bilinear transform method or the matched Z-transform method, two different methods to discretize an analog filter design.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] In the case of all-pole filters such as the Butterworth, the matched Z-transform method is equivalent to the impulse invariance method.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] For higher orders, digital filters are sensitive to quantization errors, so they are often calculated as cascaded biquad sections, plus one first-order or third-order section for odd orders.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] Here is an image showing the gain of a discrete-time Butterworth filter next to other common filter types.
[src:active-filters/butterworth-filter] The Butterworth filter rolls off more slowly around the cutoff frequency than the Chebyshev filter or the Elliptic filter, but without ripple.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] A **gyrator** is a passive, linear, lossless, two-port electrical network element proposed in 1948 by Bernard D.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] Tellegen as a hypothetical fifth linear element after the resistor, capacitor, inductor and ideal transformer.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] Unlike the four conventional elements, the gyrator is non-reciprocal.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] Gyrators permit network realizations of two-(or-more)-port devices which cannot be realized with just the four conventional elements.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] In particular, gyrators make possible network realizations of isolators and circulators.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] Gyrators do not however change the range of one-port devices that can be realized.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] Although the gyrator was conceived as a fifth linear element, its adoption makes both the ideal transformer and either the capacitor or inductor redundant.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] Thus the number of necessary linear elements is in fact reduced to three.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] Circuits that function as gyrators can be built with transistors and op-amps using feedback.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] Tellegen invented a circuit symbol for the gyrator and suggested a number of ways in which a practical gyrator might be built.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] An important property of a gyrator is that it inverts the current–voltage characteristic of an electrical component or network.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] In the case of linear elements, the impedance is also inverted.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] In other words, a gyrator can make a capacitive circuit behave inductively, a series LC circuit behave like a parallel LC circuit, and so on.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] It is primarily used in active filter design and miniaturization.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] An ideal gyrator is a linear two-port device which couples the current on one port to the voltage on the other and conversely.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] where R is the *gyration resistance* of the gyrator.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] The gyration resistance (or equivalently its reciprocal the *gyration conductance*) has an associated direction indicated by an arrow on the schematic diagram.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] By convention, the given gyration resistance or conductance relates the voltage on the port at the head of the arrow to the current at its tail.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] The voltage at the tail of the arrow is related to the current at its head by *minus* the stated resistance.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] Reversing the arrow is equivalent to negating the gyration resistance, or to reversing the polarity of either port.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] Although a gyrator is characterized by its resistance value, it is a lossless component.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] Two versions of the symbol used to represent a gyrator in single-line diagrams.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] radian) phase shift occurs for signals travelling in the direction of the arrow (or longer arrow), with no phase shift in the reverse direction.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] This leads to an alternative definition of a gyrator: a device which transmits a signal unchanged in the forward (arrow) direction, but reverses the polarity of the signal travelling in the backward direction (or equivalently, 180° phase-shifts the backward-travelling signal).
[src:active-filters/gyrator] The symbol used to represent a gyrator in one-line diagrams (where a waveguide or transmission line is shown as a single line rather than as a pair of conductors), reflects this one-way phase shift.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] However, this no longer represents a passive device.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] Tellegen named the element *gyrator* as a blend of *gyroscope* and the common device suffix *-tor* (as in resistor, capacitor, transistor etc.) The -*tor* ending is even more suggestive in Tellegen's native Dutch, where the related element *transformer* is called *transformator*.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] The gyrator is related to the gyroscope by an analogy in its behaviour.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] The analogy with the gyroscope is due to the relationship between the torque and angular velocity of the gyroscope on the two axes of rotation.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] A torque on one axis will produce a proportional change in angular velocity on the other axis and conversely.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] A mechanical–electrical analogy of the gyroscope making torque and angular velocity the analogs of voltage and current results in the electrical gyrator.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] An ideal gyrator is similar to an ideal transformer in being a linear, lossless, passive, memoryless two-port device.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] However, whereas a transformer couples the voltage on port 1 to the voltage on port 2, and the current on port 1 to the current on port 2, the gyrator cross-couples voltage to current and current to voltage.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] Cascading two gyrators achieves a voltage-to-voltage coupling identical to that of an ideal transformer.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] Cascaded gyrators of gyration resistance $R_{1}$ and $R_{2}$ are equivalent to a transformer of turns ratio $R_{1}:R_{2}$ .
[src:active-filters/gyrator] Cascading a transformer and a gyrator, or equivalently cascading three gyrators produces a single gyrator of gyration resistance $R_{1}R_{3}/R_{2}$ .
[src:active-filters/gyrator] From the point of view of network theory, transformers are redundant when gyrators are available.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] Anything that can be built from resistors, capacitors, inductors, transformers and gyrators, can also be built using just resistors, gyrators and inductors (or capacitors).
[src:active-filters/gyrator] In the two-gyrator equivalent circuit for a transformer, described above, the gyrators may be identified with the transformer windings, and the loop connecting the gyrators with the transformer magnetic core.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] The electric current around the loop then corresponds to the rate-of-change of magnetic flux through the core, and the electromotive force (EMF) in the loop due to each gyrator corresponds to the magnetomotive force (MMF) in the core due to each winding.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] The gyration resistances are in the same ratio as the winding turn-counts, but collectively of no particular magnitude.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] This is Buntenbach's capacitance–permeance analogy, or the gyrator–capacitor model of magnetic circuits.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] A gyrator can be used to transform a load capacitance into an inductance.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] At low frequencies and low powers, the behaviour of the gyrator can be reproduced by a small op-amp circuit.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] This supplies a means of providing an inductive element in a small electronic circuit or integrated circuit.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] Before the invention of the transistor, coils of wire with large inductance might be used in electronic filters.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] An inductor can be replaced by a much smaller assembly containing a capacitor, operational amplifiers or transistors, and resistors.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] This is especially useful in integrated circuit technology.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] In the circuit shown, one port of the gyrator is between the input terminal and ground, while the other port is terminated with the capacitor.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] The circuit works by inverting and multiplying the effect of the capacitor in an RC differentiating circuit, where the voltage across the resistor *R* behaves through time in the same manner as the voltage across an inductor.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] The op-amp follower buffers this voltage and applies it back to the input through the resistor *RL*.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] With *RLRC* = *L*, it can be seen that the impedance of the simulated inductor is the desired impedance in parallel with the impedance of the RC circuit.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] This is the same as a resistance *RL* in series with an inductance *L* = *RLRC*.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] There is a practical limit on the minimum value that *RL* can take, determined by the current output capability of the op-amp.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] The impedance cannot increase indefinitely with frequency, and eventually the second term limits the impedance to the value of *R*.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] Simulated elements are electronic circuits that imitate actual elements.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] Simulated elements cannot replace physical inductors in all the possible applications as they do not possess all the unique properties of physical inductors.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] The primary application for a gyrator is to reduce the size and cost of a system by removing the need for bulky, heavy and expensive inductors.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] For example, RLC bandpass filter characteristics can be realized with capacitors, resistors and operational amplifiers without using inductors.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] Thus graphic equalizers can be achieved with capacitors, resistors and operational amplifiers without using inductors because of the invention of the gyrator.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] Gyrator circuits are extensively used in telephony devices that connect to a POTS system.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] This has allowed telephones to be much smaller, as the gyrator circuit carries the DC part of the line loop current, allowing the transformer carrying the AC voice signal to be much smaller due to the elimination of DC current through it.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] Gyrators are used in most DAAs (data access arrangements).
[src:active-filters/gyrator] Circuitry in telephone exchanges has also been affected with gyrators being used in line cards.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] Gyrators are also widely used in hi-fi for graphic equalizers, parametric equalizers, discrete bandstop and bandpass filters such as rumble filters), and FM pilot tone filters.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] In microwave circuits, impedance inversion can be achieved using a quarter-wave impedance transformer instead of a gyrator.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] The quarter-wave transformer is a passive device and is far simpler to build than a gyrator.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] Unlike the gyrator, the transformer is a reciprocal component.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] The transformer is an example of a distributed-element circuit.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] Analogs of the gyrator exist in other energy domains.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] The analogy with the mechanical gyroscope has already been pointed out in the name section.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] Also, when systems involving multiple energy domains are being analysed as a unified system through analogies, such as mechanical-electrical analogies, the transducers between domains are considered either transformers or gyrators depending on which variables they are translating.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] Electromagnetic transducers translate current into force and velocity into voltage.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] In the impedance analogy however, force is the analog of voltage and velocity is the analog of current, thus electromagnetic transducers are gyrators in this analogy.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] On the other hand, piezoelectric transducers are transformers (in the same analogy).
[src:active-filters/gyrator] Thus another possible way to make an electrical passive gyrator is to use transducers to translate into the mechanical domain and back again, much as is done with mechanical filters.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] Such a gyrator can be made with a single mechanical element by using a multiferroic material using its magnetoelectric effect.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] For instance, a current carrying coil wound around a multiferroic material will cause vibration through the multiferroic's magnetostrictive property.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] This vibration will induce a voltage between electrodes embedded in the material through the multiferroic's piezoelectric property.
[src:active-filters/gyrator] The overall effect is to translate a current into a voltage resulting in gyrator action.
[src:active-filters/sallen-key-topology] The **Sallen–Key topology** is an electronic filter topology used to implement second-order active filters that is particularly valued for its simplicity.
[src:active-filters/sallen-key-topology] It is a degenerate form of a **voltage-controlled voltage-source** (**VCVS**) **filter topology**.
[src:active-filters/sallen-key-topology] A VCVS filter uses a voltage amplifier with practically infinite input impedance and zero output impedance to implement a 2-pole low-pass, high-pass, bandpass, bandstop, or allpass response.
[src:active-filters/sallen-key-topology] The VCVS filter allows high Q factor and passband gain without the use of inductors.
[src:active-filters/sallen-key-topology] A VCVS filter also has the advantage of independence: VCVS filters can be cascaded without the stages affecting each others tuning.
[src:active-filters/sallen-key-topology] A Sallen–Key filter is a variation on a VCVS filter that uses a unity gain amplifier (i.e., a buffer amplifier).
[src:active-filters/sallen-key-topology] In 1955, Sallen and Key used vacuum tube cathode follower amplifiers; the cathode follower is a reasonable approximation to an amplifier with unity voltage gain.
[src:active-filters/sallen-key-topology] Modern analog filter implementations may use operational amplifiers (also called *op amps*).
[src:active-filters/sallen-key-topology] Because of its high input impedance and easily selectable gain, an operational amplifier in a conventional non-inverting configuration is often used in VCVS implementations.
[src:active-filters/sallen-key-topology] Implementations of Sallen–Key filters often use an op amp configured as a voltage follower; however, emitter or source followers are other common choices for the buffer amplifier.
[src:active-filters/sallen-key-topology] VCVS filters are relatively resilient to component tolerance, but obtaining high Q factor may require extreme component value spread or high amplifier gain.
[src:active-filters/sallen-key-topology] Higher-order filters can be obtained by cascading two or more stages.
[src:active-filters/sallen-key-topology] The generic unity-gain Sallen–Key filter topology implemented with a unity-gain operational amplifier is shown in Figure 1.
[src:active-filters/sallen-key-topology] The following analysis is based on the assumption that the operational amplifier is ideal.
[src:active-filters/sallen-key-topology] Because the op amp is in a negative-feedback configuration, its $v_{+}$ and $v_{-}$ inputs must match (i.e., $v_{+}=v_{-}$ ).
[src:active-filters/sallen-key-topology] which typically describes a second-order linear time-invariant (LTI) system.
[src:active-filters/sallen-key-topology] If the $Z_{3}$ component were connected to ground instead of to $v_{\text{out}}$ , the filter would be a voltage divider composed of the $Z_{1}$ and $Z_{3}$ components cascaded with another voltage divider composed of the $Z_{2}$ and $Z_{4}$ components.
[src:active-filters/sallen-key-topology] The buffer amplifier bootstraps the "bottom" of the $Z_{3}$ component to the output of the filter, which will improve upon the simple two-divider case.
[src:active-filters/sallen-key-topology] This interpretation is the reason why Sallen–Key filters are often drawn with the op amp's non-inverting input below the inverting input, thus emphasizing the similarity between the output and ground.
[src:active-filters/sallen-key-topology] By choosing different passive components (e.g., resistors and capacitors) for $Z_{1}$ , $Z_{2}$ , $Z_{4}$ , and $Z_{3}$ , the filter can be made with low-pass, bandpass, and high-pass characteristics.
[src:active-filters/sallen-key-topology] where $s=j\omega =2\pi jf$ (here j denotes the imaginary unit) is the complex angular frequency, and f is the frequency of a pure sine-wave input.
[src:active-filters/sallen-key-topology] That is, a capacitor's impedance is frequency-dependent and a resistor's impedance is not.
[src:active-filters/sallen-key-topology] An example of a unity-gain low-pass configuration is shown in Figure 2.
[src:active-filters/sallen-key-topology] An operational amplifier is used as the buffer here, although an emitter follower is also effective.
[src:active-filters/sallen-key-topology] The Q factor determines the height and width of the peak of the frequency response of the filter.
[src:active-filters/sallen-key-topology] As this parameter increases, the filter will tend to "ring" at a single resonant frequency near $f_{0}$ (see "LC filter" for a related discussion).
[src:active-filters/sallen-key-topology] There are two zeros at infinity (the transfer function goes to zero for each of the s terms in the denominator).
[src:active-filters/sallen-key-topology] A designer must choose the Q and $f_{0}$ appropriate for their application.
[src:active-filters/sallen-key-topology] The Q value is critical in determining the eventual shape.
[src:active-filters/sallen-key-topology] For example, a second-order Butterworth filter, which has maximally flat passband frequency response, has a Q of $1/{\sqrt {2}}$ .
[src:active-filters/sallen-key-topology] By comparison, a value of $Q=1/2$ corresponds to the series cascade of two identical simple low-pass filters.
[src:active-filters/sallen-key-topology] Because there are 2 parameters and 4 unknowns, the design procedure typically fixes the ratio between both resistors as well as that between the capacitors.
[src:active-filters/sallen-key-topology] One possibility is to set the ratio between $C_{1}$ and $C_{2}$ as n versus $1/n$ and the ratio between $R_{1}$ and $R_{2}$ as m versus $1/m$ .
[src:active-filters/sallen-key-topology] Starting with a more or less arbitrary choice for e.g.
[src:active-filters/sallen-key-topology] C and n , the appropriate values for R and m can be calculated in favor of the desired $f_{0}$ and Q .
[src:active-filters/sallen-key-topology] In practice, certain choices of component values will perform better than others due to the non-idealities of real operational amplifiers.
[src:active-filters/sallen-key-topology] As an example, high resistor values will increase the circuit's noise production, whilst contributing to the DC offset voltage on the output of op amps equipped with bipolar input transistors.
[src:active-filters/sallen-key-topology] which shows how every $(R,C)$ combination comes with some $(m,n)$ combination to provide the same $f_{0}$ and Q for the low-pass filter.
[src:active-filters/sallen-key-topology] A similar design approach is used for the other filters below.
[src:active-filters/sallen-key-topology] The input impedance of the second-order unity-gain Sallen–Key low-pass filter is also of interest to designers.
