[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] A **state variable filter** (SVF) is a type of active filter in electronic circuits.
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] In a state-variable filter architecture the signal and its successive derivatives are treated as the core state variables of the system.
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] In state variable filters parameters like gain, cutoff frequency and Q can be independently controlled.
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] This makes it, for example, possible to build a tunable filter where the cutoff frequency is adjustable, while the gain and Q remain constant.
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] A state variable filter consists of one or more integrators, connected in some feedback configuration.
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] It is essentially used when a precise Q factor is required, as other multi-order filters are unable to provide.
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] The most common implementation sums the input signal with its integral and its double integral.
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] State variable filters can also be classified as Multiple Feedback (MFB) and Multi Feedback Loop (MFL) Filters because of the typical feedback configurations.
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] The multiple feedback architecture contributes to the reduced sensitivity to component values of state variable filters.
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] In their paper Kerwin, Huelsman and Newcomb derive a filter architecture and provide a realisation with Operational Amplifiers, using state-variable synthesis.
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] Filters of this kind, especially the version with three Operational Amplifers are known as KHN filters, or simply as state variable filters.
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] The example given below can produce simultaneous lowpass, highpass, and bandpass outputs from a single input.
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] This is a second-order (biquad, short for biquadratic) filter.
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] Its derivation comes from rearranging a high-pass filter's transfer function, which is the ratio of two quadratic functions.
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] The rearrangement reveals that one signal is the sum of integrated copies of another.
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] That is, the rearrangement reveals a state-variable-filter structure.
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] By using different states as outputs, different kinds of filters can be produced.
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] In more general state-variable-filter examples, additional filter orders are possible with more integrators (i.e., more states).
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] With an additional OpAmp (not shown) in summer configuration a bandstop output can be added by summing the lowpass and highpass output.
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] Further, an all-pass filter can be build, again with an OpAmp, by subtracting the bandpass output from the filter input.
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] The signal input is marked Vin; the LP, HP and BP outputs give the lowpass, highpass, and bandpass filtered signals respectively.
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] It can be seen that the frequency of operation and the Q factor can be varied independently.
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] This and the ability to switch between different filter responses make the state-variable filter widely used in analogue synthesizers.
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] Values for a resonance frequency of 1 kHz are Rf1 = Rf2 = 10k, C1 = C2 = 15nF and R1 = R2 = 10k.
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] Tow and Thomas independently published what is today known as the Tow-Thomas filter.
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] Other names are the Ring-of-Three Filter and the two-integrator loop.
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] Sometimes it is just called the biquad filter.
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] The filter can be considered as a rearrangement of the KHN filter and is also a biquad filter.
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] One aspect of the Tow-Thomas filter, compared to the KHN filter, is that all non-inverting OpAmp inputs are grounded.
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] This removes the effect of parasitic capacitances at all of these inputs.
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] A variant of the Tow-Thomas filter, and therefore the KHN filter, is the Åckerberg-Mossberg filter.
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] By replacing resistors in a state variable filter with multiplying DACs (MDACs) it is possible to build state variable filters where the parameters gain, cutoff frequency and Q can be independently digitally controlled.
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] It is also possible to use components like a voltage-controle amplifier (VCA) to build a digitally controlled state variable filter.
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] Further, switched capacitors can be used to replace resistors in a state variable filter (see Switched capacitor#Filters).
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] The MF10 IC and pin compatible ICs like the LMF100 and LTC1060 are examples of using a state variable filter architecture with switched capacitors.
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] The typical state variable filter is a second-order filter.
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] It is possible to conceptualize and build lower (first order) and higher-order state variable filters by removing or adding additional integrator stages (1/s stages) and corresponding feedback loops.
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] If an uneven order is desired a first order filter is needed as part of the filter cascade.
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] This can either be a first-order state variable filter or more typically some other kind of filter.
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] A first-order state variable filters can be build, although they are not widely used.
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] State variable filters are frequently used for modifying frequency response in audio signal processing.
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] At low Q settings they are often used in parametric equaliser circuits, and at high or variable Q settings to create resonant filter modules in analog synthesizers.
[src:active-filters/state-variable-filter] For manual control of frequency, Rf1 and Rf2 in the section above may be replaced by a dual potentiometer; and for voltage control, the devices U2 and U3 may be replaced by voltage controlled amplifiers or operational transconductance amplifiers.
